{% set html %}
<h2>Change Username</h2>
<p>Enter your username and password to change your username.</p>
<form>
    <div>
        <label for="username">Username</label>
        <input type="text" name="username" id="username">
    </div>
    <div>
        <label for="password">Password</label>
        <input type="password" name="password" id="password" data-password="1">
    </div>
    <div>
        <label for="show-password">
            <input type="checkbox" name="show-password" id="show-password" data-toggle="1">
            Show password
        </label>
    </div>
    <p>
        <button type="submit">Change Username</button>
    </p>
</form>
<h2>Change Password</h2>
<p>Enter your current password and new password below.</p>
<form>
    <div>
        <label for="current-password">Current Password</label>
        <input type="password" name="current-password" id="current-password" data-password="2">
    </div>
    <div>
        <label for="new-password">New Password</label>
        <input type="password" name="new-password" id="new-password" data-password="2">
    </div>
    <div>
        <label for="show-passwords">
            <input type="checkbox" name="show-passwords" id="show-passwords" data-toggle="2">
            Show passwords
        </label>
    </div>
    <p>
        <button type="submit">Change Passwords</button>
    </p>
</form>
{% endset %}

{% set description %}
In this one the comments are pretty similar to what I have thought of the other 2.
I was able to solve it without much difficulties and in a nice and concise way.

At first I had trouble identifying a way to select only those fields in the same
form as the toggle. I decided to implement an id for the form in the data attributes
and it does the job, but I don't know if it is the best method.
